plore emotional experience from perspectives other than humoral medicine. The chapters in the book seek to demonstrate how open, creative and agency-ridden the experience and interpretation of emotion could be. Taken individually, the chapters offer much-needed investigations into previously overlooked areas of emotional experience and signification; taken together, they offer a thorough re-evaluation of the cultural priorities and phenomenological principles that shaped the understanding of the emotive self in the early modern period. The Renaissance of emotion will be of particular interest to students and scholars of Shakespeare and Renaissance literature, the history of emotion, theatre and cultural history, and the history of ideas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEmotions in literature. 4aShakespeare 2018. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAffect.  aEarly Modern.  aEmbodiment.  aEmotion.  aPassion.  aRenaissance.  aShakespeare.1 aBagchi, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBain, Frederika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChamberlain, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoodin, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolbrook, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaegi, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKesson, Andy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLund, Mary Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeek, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeek, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRawnsley, Ciara, econtributor.4ctb4htt